availability.p: This resource has been designed for free consultation in association with the Sloane Consortium of UK national institutions which hold the original manuscript catalogue documents and related collections of Sir Hans Sloane. All content is reproducible as long as the source is indicated by referencing the publication and the name of the institutional owner of the original catalogue manuscript -- in this case the Natural History Museum (London).

seriesStmt.title: Enlightenment Architectures: digital texts of the manuscript catalogues of Sir Hans Sloane’s collection encoded using TEI

notesStmt.note: An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane’s Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI: http://doi.org/10.16995/olh.409 The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. These transcriptions were then fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team that is also responsible for the complete TEI markup of the transcriptions.

msItem.colophon: ‘Fossils V’ is a bound manuscript volume containing the individual separate catalogues titled ‘Fishes’; ‘Birds’; ‘Eggs’; ‘Quadrupeds’. These catalogues contain numbered entries that list and describe a number of the natural history specimens and objects collected by Sir Hans Sloane (1660-1753) between the 1680s and the 1750s. In total there are 384 folios that have been bound and numbered at a later date, a number of which contain manuscript markings on their versos. The Fishes section contains 1563 numbered entries beginning on folio 2. The Birds section contains 907 numbered entries beginning on folio 132. The Eggs section contains 272 numbered entries from folio 209. The Quadrupeds section contains 1903 numbered entries starting on folio 236. Each individual catalogue begins at number one. The entries for these lists appear on both verso and recto sides of folios with further contemporaneous additions and notes. These are usually connected to an entry by the use of an asterisk or ‘libra ponda’ (hashtag) symbol.

Hans Sloane resided in Bloomsbury Square, London and later at Chelsea Manor House. His collecting activities spanned the early modern and Enlightenment periods and are global in scope. A physician and President of the Royal Society, he was an influential figure in the intellectual developments of his time both in England and Europe. At his death his will stipulated that his collections should be bought by the State for the purposes of creating a public Museum, thereby creating the British Museum in 1753. Since that time, Sloane’s collections have been divided between the British Museum, The British Library and the Natural History Museum (London): institutions which still retain most of his collections and catalogues. The provenance of these manuscript catalogues is therefore direct and accountable.

It is estimated that Sloane made at least 50 catalogues of the various parts of his collection, including his natural history collections and library. Sloane did not publish these catalogues of his collection in his lifetime, and these digital scholarly editions created by the Enlightenment Architectures project are the first ever publications of any of these catalogues. The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. The transcription of this catalogue, Fossils V, has not been as fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team as has been done for Fossils I, Miscellanea or MS 3972 C VI; instead the TEI elements from Fossils I were automatically applied to the document in an experiment to see how much could be captured using automation. An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane's Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI:

Further information and further reading about his collections and catalogues can be found on the Reconstructing Sloane website and on the websites of the institutions he founded and which have contributed to this research project: The British Museum, The British Library, The Natural History Museum (London) and those in which he was closely involved, such as The Royal Society.

# While we lay here. our Moskito men went in
their Canoa, and struck us some Manatee or
Sea Cow. besides this Blewfields River I
have seen of the Manatee in the Bay of
Campechy, on the Coasts of Bocc de Drago &
Boca del Toro, in the River Darien. & among
the South Keys or little Islands of Cube. I have
hear'd of their being found on the North of
Jamaica, a few, & in the Rivers of Surinam in
great Multitudes, I have seen of them also at
Mindanea one of the Phillppine Islands &
on the coast of New Holland. This creature is about
the bigness of a Horse & 10 or 12 foot long. I have heard
that some have weighed above 1200 lb but I never saw any
so large. Their flesh is white , both the fat & the lean
& extraordinary sweet & wholsome meat the tail of a
young Cow is most esteem'd: but if old both head & tail are
very tough. A Calf that sucks is the most delicate meat
Privateers commonly roast them; as they do also great pieces cut
out of the Bellies of the old ones. The Skins of Manatee
is of great use to Privateers for they cut them out

# The Booby is a water fowl, somewhat less
then a Hen of a light greyish colour, it hath a strong
Bill, longer & bigger than a Crows>, and broader at the
end: her feet of flat like a Ducks feet. It is a very
simple creature, and will hardly go out of a Mans Way.
In other places they build their nests on the Ground
but here (the Isle of Aves) they build on trees; w ch.
I never saw any where else; tho' I have seen of them
in a great many places. Their flesh is black & eats
fishes, but are often eaten by the Privateers. Dampier
Voyag. Vol. 1. p. 49.

Translation We the under Written directors of the East
India Company for this Chamber, do Certify for Truth
that the Growth out of the Brains of an Elephant,
Contained in a Golden Case, was Sold at ours Sale the
13 th. May 1737. And Sent to the General East India
Company as a Present by the Zerg Sultan of I am by
in the year 1735.

Amsteldam B. scott G V. Hoven
2 d. July 1737

# Guano's are an animal like a Lizard, but
much bigger. the body is as big as a small
Mans leg and from the hind quarter the
tail grows> tapering to the end w ch. is very
small. If a man takes hold of the tail, except
very near the hind quarter, it will part &
break off in one of the joints & the Guano will
get away. They lay Eggs, as most of those
Amphibions creatures do, and are very good to
eat. Their flesh is much esteem'd by Privateers
who commonly dress them for their sick men
for they make very good bro a th. They are
of divers colours &c Dampier Voy. Vol. 1. p. 57.

# E vicino rhinoceros cernitur animal Indicum, quod etiam in
Æthiopia erat, testibus Pausaniam 9. 21. huie optime adaptatus
qui hic inscribitus PINOKEPOC, Vidi, inquit Pausanias, tawros
æthiopicos qui rhinocerotes etiam vocantur, quia in extrema
nare cornu habent, in capite vero nullum apparet cornu. Attamen
scriptores alü pene omnes rhinoceroti unicum tantum cornu dant
in nare positum. Verum hi Rhinocerotem Indicum describunt, qui
forte ab Æthiopico differat. Illud vero φU IOλó explorandum relinquo
V. Cosmas Ægyptius qui tempore Justiniani vixet, & qui iter in
æthiopiam instituerat, rhinocerotis descriptionem parat ipsique
duo cornua in naribus adscribit: neque dicit alterum cornu altero
minus esse. Schema vero quod ipso depictum dedit, cornua ferme
aqualia exhibet. Descriptio ejus qualem effert Cosmas hie non
prætermittenda. Hoc animal rhinoceros a cornibus naso hærentibus
vocatur; eo autem ambulante comua subagitantus: cum autem furore:
plenum obtuetur, cornua vibrat, ipsaque immobilia & firma consistunt,
ut etiam arborcs eradicate possit, cum maxime a fronte positæ sunt.
Terribilisninum porro est atque Elephanti maxime inimicum. Pedes
atque pellem elephanti similes habet: pellis ejus exsiccata digitorum
quatuor spissitudimen habet, qui nonnulli vomeris loco ad aratra
utuntur, illaque terram sulcant. Rhinocerotem Æthiopes propria dialeto
aru ant Harisi nuncupant, in secundo vocabulo demso spiritu alpha
pronunciantos & risi adjicientes; ut voce aru ipsum animal
significent, voce autem Harisi figuram narium atque pellem
arando opportunam indicant, hinc illi nomen imponentes. Hujusmodi
animal in Æthiopia vivum eminus conspexi mortuique pellun palea
infertam in regia consistentem, unde licuit accurate describere.
Vide Montfaucon, l'Antiq. Supplement tom. 4. p. 159.
